        <title>Explicit Instruction is...</title>
        <contents>&lt;div style="width: 716px;"&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;img width="200" height="200" style="float: right; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px;" alt="Smiling male student in class with other adult students" src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/LTA-EI-S1b-flex-response-smilingman.jpg" /&gt;Flexible&lt;/strong&gt; - Explicit instruction components can be combined with other types of instruction such as collaborative learning and contextualized teaching.  As teachers, we will not use every component of explicit instruction in every lesson. But knowing the &lt;em&gt;how&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;why&lt;/em&gt; of explicit instruction allows us to offer more effective instruction that will specifically target our most vulnerable learners.   &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Responsive&lt;/strong&gt; - Explicit instruction does not mean rote and mechanical instruction. It is based in, and responsive to, the needs of your adult learners. EI teaches students how to engage in &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;efficient learning behaviors&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="background-color: #ffff00;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style="background-color: #ffffff; color: #993300;"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
